            <div type="translation">
            <p>In the year [- - -], Priests of the Olympian Zeus and of the Saviour Gods. [- - -],
                    [the Priest] of the ancestors of the King, [- - -]ulos son of Epikrates. [The
                    Priest of] King Demetrios, Herakleides son of Sarapion.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription is the only Hellenistic text documenting the religious life of
                    Scythopolis, and one of only two Hellenistic inscription recovered from Tel Beth
                    Shean. The stone was discovered in a cistern on the tel; a temple stood on the
                    site in imperial times (Romano 2023). Since the stele is not made of the local
                    white limestone, it must have been brought in from elsewhere (Mahoney 2023). The
                    identification of the Theoi Soteres is debated, perhaps simply referring to the
                    guardin gods of the Seleucid dynasty (Mahoney 2023). As for the individuals
                    named on the inscription: Epikrates may be the ancestor of Epikrates who was
                    general under Antiochos IX Kyzikenos (111-107 BCE); Herakleides bears a common
                    Greek-Egyptian name; the King Demetrios mentioned in line 7 is Demetrios II
                    Nikator, the son of Demetrios I Soter. The latter obtained the throne with the
                    help of Cretan and Aegean mercenaries, and the support of Ptolemy VI  was also
                    significant. Mahoney 2023 suggests that the inscription should be placed within
                    the context of the struggles between Demetrios II Nikator and other aspirant
                    rulers, namely Alexander Balas and Diodotos Tryphon, and later against his
                    brother Antiochos VII Sidetes. The stele may have remained on the tel during the
                    Roman period and continuously through the fourth century CE. Mahoney 2023
                    further argues that the inscription, by pointing toward the Hellenistic past of
                    Scythopolis, continued to shape the city's Hellenistic identity through its link
                    with the Scythopolitcan progonoi, the Seleucids.</p></div>
            

